>What is netorare supposed to do as a trope or subgenre?
Depends entirely on how the author wants to use it.
>What is it that makes netorare what it is?
In its most basic form it's cheating from the perspective of the one being cheated on and/or from the perspective of the one doing the cheating but with considerable focus still on the one being cheated on.
>Is there a plot structure specific to it?
No. So long as the main focus of the story is from the person being cheated on then it's ntr.
>Is there an assortment of necessary characters?
Yes. The minimum is a couple or pair of people that are shown or supposed to have romantic or sexual interest in one another and another person for one of those people in that couple or pair to cheat on the other with.
>Is it necessary to distinguish it from cheating and netori?
Not really. All three are adultery, the only real differences are perspectives, where netori is told from the perspective of the third party as opposed to ntr, and characters, where cheating can be just two people where it is mentioned that one of them has a significant other.
>Convince me it deserves respect.
At its purest form it's nothing more than a device to be used in a story, no different from any other device. The question of respect lies solely in the people who use it in their story and why they use it in their story as well as who likes it and why they like it.
